{{Infobox CanadianMP | honorific-prefix = | name =Richard Cannings |honorific-suffix = [[House of Commons of Canada|MP]] | image = | imagesize = 200px | riding = [[South Okanagan—West Kootenay]] | parliament = Canadian | term_start =October 19, 2015 | term_end = | predecessor =[[Alex Atamanenko]] | successor = | birth_date ={{Birth date and age|1954|3|31}} | birth_place =[[Penticton]], [[British Columbia]] | death_date = | death_place = | profession =Biologist, author | party = [[New Democratic Party]] | residence = | footnotes = | spouse = | children= |}}
'''Richard J. "Dick" Cannings''' {{post-nominals|country=CAN|MP}} (born March 31, 1954) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] politician, who was elected to represent the [[electoral district (Canada)|riding]] of [[South Okanagan—West Kootenay]] in the [[House of Commons of Canada]] in the [[Canadian federal election, 2015]].<ref>http://globalnews.ca/news/2285544/ndp-claims-south-okanagan-west-kootenay/</ref> An alumnus of [[Memorial University of Newfoundland]] and the [[University of British Columbia]], he is a [[biologist]] and author.<ref>http://www.abcbookworld.com/view_author.php?id=1228</ref>
Cannings was appointed the NDP Critic for Post-Secondary Education as well as the Deputy Critic for [[Minister of Natural Resources (Canada)|Natural Resources]] in the [[42nd Canadian Parliament]].<ref name="NDP 42nd Critics">{{cite web | url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/ndp-critics-list-mulcair-thursday-1.3315431 | title=Tom Mulcair taps Nathan Cullen, Charlie Angus, Guy Caron for top critic roles | publisher=[[The Canadian Press]] | work=[[CBC News]] | date=12 November 2015 | accessdate=12 November 2015 | author=Kirkup, Kristy}}</ref>
